page_title: Fine-tuning function calls with Azure OpenAI Service
page_description: Learn how to improve function calling performance with Azure OpenAI fine-tuning
chunk_title: Customize model responses to function outputs
chunk_content: Customize model responses to function outputsFine-tuning based on function calling examples can also be used to improve the model's response to function outputs. To accomplish this, you include examples consisting of function response messages and assistant response messages where the function response is interpreted and put into context by the assistant.```json{    "messages": [        {"role": "user", "content": "What is the weather in San Francisco?"},        {"role": "assistant", "function_call": {"name": "get_current_weather", "arguments": "{\"location\": \"San Francisco, USA\", \"format\": \"celcius\"}"}}        {"role": "function", "name": "get_current_weather", "content": "21.0"},        {"role": "assistant", "content": "It is 21 degrees celsius in San Francisco, CA"}    ],    "functions": [...] // same as before}```As with the example before, this example is artificially expanded for readability. The actual entry in the `.jsonl` training file would be a single line:```jsonl{"messages": [{"role": "user", "content": "What is the weather in San Francisco?"}, {"role": "assistant", "function_call": {"name": "get_current_weather", "arguments": "{\"location\": \"San Francisco, USA\", \"format\": \"celcius\"}"}}, {"role": "function", "name": "get_current_weather", "content": "21.0"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "It is 21 degrees celsius in San Francisco, CA"}], "functions": []}```
